workflow EnrichRunner
  goal: "Loop through every thin sprint in .ai/sprints/ and enrich it via Sonnet so the local-gen runner can transcribe each one. A sprint is 'thin' if it lacks a `## Interface contract` section."
  start: Start
  exit: Exit

  defaults
    provider: anthropic
    fidelity: summary:medium
    max_restarts: 50

  agent Start
    label: Start
    prompt:
      Begin enrichment runner. Will loop through every thin sprint and enrich it in place.

  agent Exit
    label: Exit
    prompt:
      Enrichment runner complete.

  tool find_next_thin
    label: "Find Next Thin Sprint"
    timeout: 10s
    command:
      set -eu
      if [ ! -d .ai/sprints ]; then
        printf 'no_sprints'
        exit 0
      fi
      target=""
      for f in .ai/sprints/SPRINT-*.md; do
        [ -f "$f" ] || continue
        if ! grep -q '^## Interface contract' "$f" 2>/dev/null; then
          target="$f"
          break
        fi
      done
      if [ -z "$target" ]; then
        printf 'all_enriched'
        exit 0
      fi
      cp "$target" .ai/sprints/TARGET-SPRINT.md
      base=$(basename "$target" .md)
      printf 'next-%s' "$base"

  agent no_sprints_exit
    label: "No Sprints Found"
    prompt:
      No .ai/sprints/ directory found. Run spec_to_sprints.dip first to produce thin sprint docs.

  agent Enrich
    label: "Enrich one sprint (Sonnet)"
    model: claude-sonnet-4-6
    provider: anthropic
    max_turns: 8
    prompt:
      You are working in `run.working_dir`.

      Your job: take ONE thin sprint doc and enrich it into a precise,
      machine-executable specification that a small local LLM (qwen3.6:35b
      via Ollama, no internet, no tool calls, single generation pass per file)
      can transcribe into working code with zero judgment calls. The executing
      model copies — it does not invent.

      ## Worked example: thin → enriched

      The example below shows the transformation in concrete form. Note what
      sections are added, what level of verbatim detail, what pinned versions,
      what exact signatures, what test names. Match this density and style
      when you enrich the target sprint, adapted to the target's language
      and project conventions.

      ### BEFORE — thin sprint (the shape you receive)

      ```markdown
      # Sprint 001 — Platform foundation & pilot seed
      ## Scope
      Stand up the application skeleton, shared test harness, core schema, and deterministic pilot-location fixtures so all later sprints build on the same baseline.
      ## Non-goals
      No volunteer-facing or staff-facing workflow is considered complete in this sprint.
      ## Requirements
      FR1, FR11
      ## Dependencies
      None
      ## Expected Artifacts
      - db/migrations/001_init.sql
      - src/domain/schema.ts
      - src/routes/health.ts
      - src/bootstrap/test_app.ts
      - tests/contracts/health_and_schema.test.ts
      - tests/fixtures/pilot_location.json
      ## DoD
      - [x] Write failing test for app boot, health route, and base schema.
      - [x] Create base tables for volunteers, volunteer_profiles, locations, stations, shifts, opportunities, registrations, group_registrations, waivers, orientation_completions, checkins, assignments, message_events, crm_links, crm_match_exceptions, pathway_submissions, audit_events, consent_events, and privacy_requests.
      - [x] Add a health endpoint that returns app and dependency status.
      - [x] Add deterministic pilot seed data for one location, one published shift, and two stations.
      - [x] Add shared test bootstrap utilities so downstream sprints reuse the same seeded baseline.
      - [x] Pass health and schema contract tests.
      ## Validation
      - `npm run db:migrate`
      - `npm run seed:pilot`
      - `npm test -- tests/contracts/health_and_schema.test.ts`
      ```

      ### AFTER — enriched sprint (the shape you must produce)

      ```markdown
      # Sprint NNN — [Title] (enriched spec)

      ## Scope
      [One paragraph. Expands the thin scope with language, runtime, and package names filled in.]

      ## Runtime and conventions
      - **[Language/runtime + version]** — test runner, module system, build tool
      - **[Primary library or framework]** — version pinned (e.g. `somelibrary v1.2.3`)
      - **[Key conventions]** — error-wrapping style, file layout, naming rules

      ## Interface contract

      ```[language]
      // path/to/file.[ext]
      [ExactSignature(param Type) ReturnType]

      // path/to/types.[ext]
      [Full struct/type/interface definitions go HERE — verbatim — not in Algorithm notes]

      // path/to/other.[ext]
      [AnotherSignature(param Type) ReturnType]
      ```

      ## Imports per file

      **`path/to/file.[ext]`**
      ```[language]
      [exact import block — copy verbatim when writing this file]
      ```

      **`path/to/other.[ext]`**
      ```[language]
      [exact import block — copy verbatim when writing this file]
      ```

      ## Algorithm notes

      Two-tier policy — pick tier per function to keep enriched length ≤ 500 lines:

      **Tier A — verbatim body (use for AT MOST 3 functions per sprint).**
      Reserve for functions where exact text matters: parsing, formatting,
      tricky control flow, or where a numbered description would lose fidelity.

      **FunctionName(params) ReturnType:** Copy this body exactly:
      ```[language]
      [verbatim implementation — no paraphrasing]
      ```

      **Tier B — signature + numbered steps (use for everything else,
      including all CRUD, glue, wiring, and trivial accessors).**

      **AnotherFunction(params) ReturnType:**
      1. Step one — literal operation (name the exact call, arg, or field)
      2. Step two — literal operation
      3. ... 3 to 8 steps total; each step unambiguous

      Type, struct, interface, and constant definitions belong in
      `## Interface contract`, not here. Do NOT repeat them in Algorithm notes.

      ## Test plan

      ```
      TestFunctionA/subtest name one
      TestFunctionA/subtest name two
      TestFunctionB/subtest name three
      ```

      ## New files
      - `path/to/new_file.[ext]`
      - `path/to/another.[ext]`

      ## Modified files
      - `path/to/existing.[ext]` — describe the change in a few words
      - `path/to/prior_sprint_test.[ext]` — RECONCILE: replace `old assertion`
        with `new assertion` (this sprint changed [thing] from [old] to [new],
        and this prior-sprint test asserts on it)
      ```

      ## Steps

      1. bash: `cat inputs/spec.md 2>/dev/null || cat .ai/spec_analysis.md 2>/dev/null || echo "(no spec available — anchor strictly to the thin sprint and prior enriched sprints; do NOT invent scope)"`
         — read the full product spec for ground truth on exact types, function
         behaviour, and conventions. Falls back to .ai/spec_analysis.md if
         present, then to a no-spec mode where you must rely only on the thin
         sprint and prior enriched sprints (Step 2).
      2. bash: `for f in .ai/sprints/SPRINT-*.md; do grep -q '^## Interface contract' "$f" 2>/dev/null && { echo "=== $f ==="; cat "$f"; }; done`
         — read previously-enriched sprints (those with an Interface contract
         section) in this project for context on what packages, conventions,
         and file layouts prior sprints established.
      3. bash: `cat .ai/sprints/TARGET-SPRINT.md` — the ONE thin sprint to enrich.
         The first heading line names the sprint id (e.g. "# Sprint 003 — ...").
      4. Call the `write` tool to save the enriched sprint to
         `.ai/sprints/SPRINT-<id>.md` (zero-pad the id to 3 digits, overwriting
         the thin original), following the same structure and depth as the
         AFTER example above, adapted for THIS sprint and the target project's
         language.

      ## Rules

      - The enriched sprint must be self-contained. The executing local model
        needs nothing else to produce correct, passing code.
      - Match the AFTER example's structural depth: pinned module versions,
        exact import blocks per file, exact test function names.
      - **AFTER is illustrative, not canonical.** It shows ONE language's
        section list. Add target-appropriate sections this sprint actually
        needs (e.g. a dependency-declaration section for projects with
        manifest-based dep management; a schema section for migration-bearing
        sprints; a build-steps section for sprints with codegen). Drop
        sections that don't apply. Don't over-enumerate — only what this
        sprint needs.
      - **Declarative state vs hand-patched artifacts.** Some files are
        produced by language tooling (lockfiles like `go.sum`, `package-lock.json`,
        `Cargo.lock`, `poetry.lock`; resolver-managed parts of dep manifests;
        build outputs; vendored caches; generated code). For those, declare
        the desired state and provide the exact CLI command the executor
        should run (e.g. `go get pkg@version`, `npm install pkg@version`,
        `cargo add pkg`, `pip install pkg==version`, `make migrate`,
        `protoc <args>`). NEVER list lockfiles or other tool-output artifacts
        under `## Modified files` for hand-patching — qwen guesses bytes
        that won't match what the resolver downloads, breaking verification.
        For dep-manifest files where humans hand-edit a section (e.g. the
        scripts block of `package.json`), prefer the install command over
        a hand-patch when one exists.
      - **Length cap: ≤ 500 lines total.** Output-token ceiling is 8192;
        going over truncates the doc mid-write and breaks transcription.
        If you feel the urge to inline a 4th verbatim body, switch it to
        Tier B (signature + numbered steps) instead.
      - Type/struct/interface/constant definitions live in
        `## Interface contract` only — never duplicated in Algorithm notes.
      - Do not invent scope: every artifact, DoD item, and type must trace
        back to the thin sprint, the spec, or a prior enriched sprint.
      - File-listing format: use `## New files` and `## Modified files`
        headers (not `## Expected Artifacts`). Each entry is a file path
        (with filename), never a bare directory.
      - **Cross-sprint reconciliation:** when this sprint changes a string,
        signature, command-line flag, output format, or any other behavior
        that a TEST in a prior sprint asserts on, you MUST list those prior-
        sprint test files under `## Modified files` with the exact replacement
        text inline (`RECONCILE: replace 'old' with 'new'`). The exec pipeline
        treats anything under `## Modified files` as a patchable file, so this
        is the channel for cross-sprint test fixture updates. Read the prior
        enriched sprints (Step 2 above) to find tests that may need updating.
        Common triggers: changing a CLI usage string, renaming an exported
        function, changing a JSON field name, adding new sub-commands.

      You have ONLY these tools: bash (read-only), write.
      Do NOT use: edit, read, glob, grep_search, apply_patch.

  tool cleanup_target
    label: "Cleanup Target"
    timeout: 5s
    command:
      set -eu
      rm -f .ai/sprints/TARGET-SPRINT.md
      printf 'cleanup-done'

  edges
    Start -> find_next_thin
    find_next_thin -> Exit              when ctx.tool_stdout = all_enriched   label: all_enriched
    find_next_thin -> no_sprints_exit   when ctx.tool_stdout = no_sprints     label: no_sprints
    find_next_thin -> Enrich            when ctx.tool_stdout != all_enriched  label: next
    no_sprints_exit -> Exit
    Enrich -> cleanup_target
    cleanup_target -> find_next_thin    restart: true
